  "text": "Django migration squashing compliance is implemented across five core Python source files that handle the generation, tracking, validation, and application of squashed migrations.\n\n**Squash Migration Generator:**\nThe `django/core/management/commands/squashmigrations.py` file implements the squash migration command. The `Command.handle()` method is the main entry point that orchestrates the squashing process. It uses `find_migration()` to locate the migrations to be squashed, collects their operations and dependencies, optimizes them using `MigrationOptimizer`, and creates a new migration with a `replaces` attribute listing the original migrations being replaced.\n\n**Replaced Migrations Tracking:**\nThe `django/db/migrations/migration.py` file defines the base `Migration` class with the `replaces` attribute (line 42). This attribute stores a list of migration names that the current migration replaces. During migration loading, `django/db/migrations/loader.py` identifies migrations with non-empty `replaces` attributes and stores them in the `replacements` dictionary (lines 293-298).\n\n**Dependency Graph Validation After Squashing:**\nThe `django/db/migrations/graph.py` file implements the `MigrationGraph` class that represents the digraph of all migrations. The graph contains `Node` objects representing migrations and edges representing dependencies. When replacements are processed, the graph is modified using two key methods:\n\n1. `remove_replaced_nodes()` (line 125) - Removes the old replaced migration nodes and redirects dependencies to point to the replacement node instead. This ensures dependent migrations no longer reference the squashed migrations.\n\n2. `remove_replacement_node()` (line 161) - Handles the inverse operation when a replacing migration cannot be used (e.g., when partially applied). It removes the replacement node and remaps children to the replaced nodes.\n\nAfter graph modification, `validate_consistency()` (line 198) is called to ensure there are no dummy nodes remaining, and `ensure_not_cyclic()` (line 271) validates that no circular dependencies exist.\n\n**Squash Completeness Check:**\nThe `django/db/migrations/loader.py` file implements the `replace_migration()` method (line 235) which processes each replacement migration. It recursively resolves all replaced migration keys using `_resolve_replaced_migration_keys()` (line 224), then checks whether all replaced migrations are either fully applied or completely unapplied (lines 251-270).\n\nThe completeness validation continues with `check_consistent_history()` (line 344) which uses `all_replaced_applied()` (line 372) to recursively verify that all migrations replaced by a squash migration are marked as applied in the database before allowing the squash migration to be used. This ensures data consistency and prevents partial application states.\n\n**Exception Handling:**\nThe `django/db/migrations/exceptions.py` file defines critical exception classes used throughout the squashing process:\n- `NodeNotFoundError` - Raised when a dependency references a non-existent migration\n- `CircularDependencyError` - Raised when circular dependencies are detected\n- `InconsistentMigrationHistory` - Raised when applied migrations have unapplied dependencies\n\nTogether, these components form a comprehensive migration squashing compliance system that ensures squashed migrations maintain proper dependency resolution, prevent circular dependencies, and guarantee data consistency through careful validation of replacement status."
}

